In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims November as National Diabetes Month. He highlights the importance of educating Americans about the risk factors and warning signs of diabetes, as well as honoring those living with or lost to the disease. The article discusses the severe health problems and complications that can arise from diabetes, such as heart disease, stroke, vision loss, kidney disease, nerve damage, and amputation. It emphasizes that obesity is one of the significant risk factors for Type 2 diabetes and encourages Americans to engage in regular physical activity, maintain a healthy weight, and make nutritious food choices to reduce their chances of developing the disease. The article also mentions the efforts to combat childhood obesity through the "Let's Move!" initiative led by First Lady Michelle Obama. Additionally, it highlights the provisions of the Affordable Care Act that aim to reverse the increase in diabetes and provide care for those with the disease, such as prohibiting insurance companies from denying coverage or excluding benefits for children with pre-existing conditions like diabetes. The law also requires diabetes screenings to be provided free of charge and covers the cost of medical nutritional therapy for seniors with diabetes. The article concludes by commending those fighting against diabetes and calling upon various individuals and institutions to participate in activities that raise awareness and help prevent, treat, and manage the disease.